SUMMARY:Modlin Center for the Arts (Richmond\, VA)
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20241016
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20241019
X-FUNAMBOL-ALLDAY:1
X-MICROSOFT-CDO-ALLDAYEVENT:1
DESCRIPTION:Modlin Center for the Arts\, University of Richmond\, VA
  Presenter will provide local ground transportation as agreed\, hotel ac
 commodations\, hospitality\, rider\n
  requirements and/or backline as agreed.\n
  ASSISTANT DIRECTOR: Shannon Hooker 804.287.6599 (office)\, 910.352.2472
  (cell)\n
  PRODUCTION MANAGER: Sean Farrell 804.287.6898 (office)\, 804.433.7842 (
 cell)\n
  ARTIST SERVICES: Jo Bachman 804.287.6607 (office)\, 804.338.7523 (cell)
 \n
  \nVENUE INFO:\n
    tel:+1 804-289-8980\n
    http://modlin.richmond.edu/\n
  \n*************************************\nSCHEDULE:\n
  11:00 AM EDT: JL DRIVER pick up artists at hotel\, transport to Modlin
 Center\n  Text/Call: Jo Bachman (804.338.7523) or Shannon Hooker (910.35
 2.2472 cell)\n
  \n----------------------------------------\n
  11:30 AM - 1:00 PM EDT: 10/16 Get Out the Vote Block Party on The Forum
 \n  Wed\, Oct 16\n
  11:30am arrive\n
  12:00 – 1:00 pm Get Out the Vote Block Party on The Forum\n
  Celebration and testimonial event on the importance of voting. Teaser p
 erformance of 3 songs and band statement about activism and voter engage
 ment.\n
  (outdoor space /free speech area\; has power\; 50-100 university partic
 ipants)\n
  The event will have tabling and an open mic for community/student leade
 rs on why it’s important to be engaged.\n
  \n----------------------------------------\n
  1:15 PM - 2:15 PM EDT: 10/16 Lunch in Dining Hall\n--------------------
 --------------------\n
  4:30 PM - 5:45 PM EDT: 10/16  College Class Visit with Latinx On Stage
  students\n  4:45 – 5:45 Class Visit with Latinx On Stage\n
  (classroom with projector\, flexible seating\n
  Patricia Hererra\, associate professor\n
  Department of Theatre and Dance\, American Studies and Women\, Gender\,
  & Sexuality Studies\n
  14 undergraduate students\, most non-performing arts students. This cou
 rse examines the evolving formation of Latina/o identity in Broadway and
  community productions as well as popular culture with special attention
  to issues of globalization\, migration\, and transculturation.\n
  An interactive workshop to discuss how the band uses song and lyrics to
  highlight immigration struggles\, cultural identity\, and privlege. Wor
 kshop to include the performance of a couple of acoustic songs\, discuss
 ion\, and some writing exercises for participants to explore their own n
 arratives.\n
  \n----------------------------------------\n
  10/17/2024 8:30 AM - 10/17/2024 9:30 AM EDT: DENISE & HECTOR ONLY- JL p
 ick up & Presentation w/Provost Leadership\n----------------------------
 ------------\n
  10/17/2024 10:00 AM EDT: JL pick up artists at hotel\n-----------------
 -----------------------\n
  10/17/2024 10:30 AM - 10/17/2024 11:30 AM EDT: 10/17 #1 Class Visit wit
 h 1st Year Seminar: Meaning and Value\n  10:30 – 11:30am  Class Visit
 with First Year Seminar: Meaning and Value (classroom with projector\; 2
 0 university students) –\n
  Discussion about Las Cafeteras as organizers and music makers with vide
 o to share music.\n
  Dr. H. Bondurant\,\n
  20 first year students\; The course explores what makes a person's life
  go well. Specific questions the class will consider are: That is worth
 pursuing? What is the relationship between a good life and a life of ple
 asure\, happiness and virtue? What are some barries to living a good lif
 e? What is the best way to think about death? Is there any meaning or pu
 rpose in human existence and can such meaning be found without a faith o
 r religion? What role does art or creativity\, or hope play in finding m
 eaning in life?\n
  \n----------------------------------------\n
  10/17/2024 11:30 AM - 10/17/2024 12:00 PM EDT: 10/17 - 11:30am  LUNCH (
 provided by presenter)\n----------------------------------------\n
  10/17/2024 12:00 PM - 10/17/2024 1:00 PM EDT: 10/17 #2 Class Visit with
  1st Year Seminar: Meaning and Value\n----------------------------------
 ------\n
  10/17/2024 1:20 PM - 10/17/2024 2:45 PM EDT: 10/17  #3 Class Visit with
  Stories Matter: Listening and Telling\n  1:30 – 2:45 Class Visit with
  Stories Matter: Listening and Telling (Latin American & Iberian Studies
  course) – role of music as healing (classroom with projector\; 20 uni
 versity students). Writing exercises around the intersectionality of ide
 ntity. Sing or share music video.\n
  The professor will introduce the artist visit with an article on music
 and healing. Interactive discussion on storytelling through music. Intro
 duce some writing exercises around the intersectionality of identity and
  sing or share a music video.\n
  Dr. Karina Vazquez\, Teaching Faculty of Latin American\, Latino\, and
 Iberian\n
  12 undergraduate students in liberal arts disciplines. The course\, tau
 ght in Spanish\, explores the events and contexts of illness\, the role
 of care and caregivers\, theories and belief about the origins of diseas
 e\, our relationship with death with a particular focus on how learning
 about telling stories and learning how to listen for stories related to
 illness and pain reconnects patients and health\n
  practioners. Students will read and discuss medicine narratives\n
  Studies & Director of Community-Based Learning for LALIS\n
  \n----------------------------------------\n
  10/17/2024 2:50 PM - 10/17/2024 4:15 PM EDT: 10/17 #4 Class Visit: Peop
 le’s History of Music\n  3:00 – 4:15 Class Visit Anthropology of Mus
 ic (combined session with Intro to Philosophy) – People’s History o
 f Music (studio classroom with projection\; 35 university students) Dis
 cussion with a couple of songs\n
  People's History of Music workshop - begin by covering the history of s
 on jarocho and how this style comes into the band's music with demonstra
 tion of a couple of songs\, and then concluding with discussion and exam
 ples exploring the role of music in social movements.\n
  Dr. Andy McGraw\, Associate Professor of Music and Chair\, Department o
 f Music\n
  Dr. Hannah Bondurant\, Visiting Professor of Philosophy\n
  35 undergraduate students in liberal arts disciplines. The course explo
 res significant topics and issues\, methodologies\, and theories applica
 ble to historical and ethnographic music studies. Taught through examina
 tion of a broad cross section of musical styles\, genres\, and tradition
 s. Intro to Philosophy students will join this class session to learn ab
 out Las Cafeteras as organizers and music makers.\n
  \n----------------------------------------\n
